Foot-and-mouth disease, Tunisia
-------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 24 Dec 218 from Dr Malek Zrelli, [Director General, General Directorate of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture], Tunis, Tunisia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 15 Dec 2018
Date of confirmation of the event: 21 Dec 2018
Reason for notification: recurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 26 May 2017
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Foot and mouth disease virus
Serotype: O
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks (4)
Outbreak 1: El khalsa, El khalsa, Siliana Nord, Siliana
Date of start of the outbreak: 15 Dec 2018
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 50 / 5 / 0 / 0 / 0
Sheep / 20 / 0 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: These are unvaccinated young animals born after the end of the vaccination campaign and that belong to horse dealers.

Outbreak 2: Maghdoudch, Maghdoudch, Kasserine Sud, Kasserine
Date of start of the outbreak: 15 Dec 2018
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Sheep / 150 / 34 / 14 / 0 / 0
Affected population: These are unvaccinated young animals born after the end of the vaccination campaign and that belong to horse dealers.

Outbreak 3: Saloul, Saloul, Ain Drahem, Jendouba
Date of start of the outbreak: 17 Dec 2018
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 7 / 7 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: These are unvaccinated young animals born after the end of the vaccination campaign and that belong to horse dealers.

Outbreak 4: El makarem, El makarem, Sidi Bouzid Est, Sidi Bouzid
Date of start of the outbreak: 19 Dec 2018
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 14 / 5 / 1 / 0 / 0
Affected population: These are unvaccinated young animals born after the end of the vaccination campaign and that belong to horse dealers.

Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 4
Total animals affected
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 71 / 17 / 1 / 0 / 0
Sheep / 170 / 34 / 14 /0 / 0
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / 23.94 / 1.41 / 5.88 / 1.41
Sheep / 20 / 8.24 / 41.18 /8.24
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive.
Epidemiological comments: The FMD vaccination campaign for cattle and small ruminants for the year 2018 was completed last September. The vaccine used is a trivalent vaccine with valences of A, O, and SAT2 with more than 6 PD50.

Control measures
Measures applied: surveillance outside containment and/or protection zone; surveillance within containment and/or protection zone; vaccination permitted (if a vaccine exists); no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: vaccination in response to the outbreak(s)

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Tunisia Veterinary investigation Institute (IRVT) (national laboratory) / Cattle / real-time reverse transcriptase/polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 21 Dec 2018 / Positive
Tunisia Veterinary investigation Institute (IRVT) (national laboratory) / Sheep / typing ELISA / 21 Dec 2018 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreaks can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

